Banded on 6/17/2015.  Found dead on side of house on 6/18/2015
this is a very long comment, because some people really like to add long comments and here I am giving them the opportunity to do sol.
Returned to yard, announcing his arrival with lots of song. Monitored him for 15 minutes - he checked out all the bushes, took a drink from the birdbath - appears to be looking for a nest spot.
feeding young in nest in multiflora rose bush in neighbor's backyard - submitted nest form for that nest and harvested 8/8/18
With food in beak, flying around behind the shed, there must be a nest in the arbor vitae but I can't find it.
singing by nest box with wire mesh predator guard and all over the place - that nest box had both HOWR nests this season
Feeding young in box with an unbanded female (can't believe there are still unbanded HOWR in this yard) - this nest was harvested and data submitted 8/8/18
Male banded 2018. Seen in side yard along with a bunch of juveniles.
This male robin banded this year 2018. A mate to a banded female from 2017. Observing their nest in my front yard. This date male seen collecting food and feeding young.
Seen carrying food to a possible nest at the top of a tall Oak tree. I was not able to see where the nest was but I saw this robin carrying food often.
After not seeing the Robins for at least a week, this evening saw a group of 5 and this one was in the group. Probably the last time seeing this fall.
Male robin that was banded this year. Seen in my back yard with about 12 other robins. Maybe another banded robin in this group but I was only able to identify this one.
Feathers on chest looking much better than when I saw her 3 weeks ago, must have been molting. Seen with a group of other Robins in the back yard.
Have not seen her for a while. This date saw banded male/ her mate. This female was banded in 2017 and recaught this year 2018. Chest feathers looking very scruffy.
Female seen carrying food to top of a tall oak. Can not see a nest but she is carrying food often to same location.
Banded in 2017. This female feeding young at a nest in my front yard. Male from this pair just banded in 2018.
This female banded in 2017 is now nest building in my side yard. A male robin not banded appears to be hanging out with this one. Nest will be observed but too high up to count eggs.
Seen nest building in my front yard. Her leg bands were muddy. This is the second nest for this bird. First nest failed earlier in May.
This Robin was banded in my yard in 2016 and this is the second year he has come back!
Has been seen consistently in my back yard. Not sure what female he is paired with this year. For sure he is not hanging around the banded female he was paired with last year.
this one was banded in 2016. seen singing in yard.
Seen in backyard, neighbor, This bird was banded in 2016.

This female banded in 2016 and not seen again by me till this year. I have been watching this female on a nest in my next yard. This is the date she was last seen feeding the young nestlings in the nest. Nest failed for unknown reason. I did not see her again, nor the nestlings.
Banded 2018. This male has made a nest in an open box hanging on my porch. Waiting to see if nesting progresses. This date male is seen singing many places near the nest box.
Male banded 2018. Feeding nestlings in nestbox on my front porch. And singing!
Male banded 2018. With female and 4 fledglings. Feeding and singing.
Seen in my side yard by the woodpile, singing!!! This is the male that was banded this year and nested on my front porch.
This female banded 6/20/18. Has been on nest at a nest box in my front yard. On nest at this date.
This female banded this year. Feeding young in nest box in my front yard. Young will fledge today. This was the last I saw of all. When babies fledged I didn't see them again..
Male banded in 2017. In the birdbath and singing.
7:30 am Singing in the back yard. Has been singing in the area and also feeding young in a nest in neighbors front yard.

This banded male from 2017 has been seen singing through out my yard for the month of April. He also has been seen with another song sparrow (not banded) who was collecting nesting material and building a nest in next door neighbors yard shrub. This will be monitored to check.
Bird is incubating 4 eggs in a nest 4' off ground in bushy area. Eggs first noticed on 5/13. Approach to nest is covered with poison ivy so I monitor rarely.
275034995, Bird was hanging out with chickadee banded 269087755with whom she fledged young last summer. No other chickadees were present.
269087755, Bird was hanging out with chickadee banded 278093372 with whom he fledged young last summer. No other chickadees were present.
Chickadee checked out two nest boxes today. Both are already occupied. This bird successfully nested last year in one of the nest boxes he checked today.
Adult cardinal fed a fledgling that was perched in a tree.
This female is almost always seen with male 273155803. Both birds have been observed several times since they were banded in my yard on 05/10/18.
Green band on left leg is missing. This bird was netted with female 273155802 in summer 2018. He and the female continue to be together, today they were at feeder together.
Wren banded 06/25/18. Wren has been singing on or near a nest box bearing 7 house wren eggs.
Bird is consistently singing with a few yards of the nest box in he partnered to fledge two birds in 2016.

"If this sighting is correct, this bird would be from 2012.  It was a female and I am certain it had a yellow white combo.  There are many large, older trees being cut down and it is possible that birds are shifting.  My feeders run all year round.   So she could have come in.  The pond is working and there is a bird bath.  There is abundant cover and seed.  I was startled while gardening, and she was moving fast.   Will be on the look out for her again.   I had a ""drop-in"" bird come to the garden. It was smaller than others, yellow head and chest, shorter tail, some kind of warbler.  I could not hear a song, but later in the day I saw it and heard a song.  Am checking Audubon recordings and cannot recognize it.  It was not a Prothonoatary Warbler as this bird had a definite chain of notes in a song.  I get ""drop-ins"" now.  Will be on the lookout."

The Cardinal was feeding at the window feeder with safflower. Red-headed finches, Chickadees, House Sparrows, Carolina Wrens have been seen. The garden is asleep. Fox sighted at pond at 11 p.m. The neighbor's dog was barking furiously with a frightful tone. I had hoped to see St. Nicholas (the Czech Santo who is skinny),who comes the night of December 5, but was more surprised. Rats and squirrels sighted. The Juncos have come. An immature Red-tailed hawk was sighted at Tuckahoe Park while I was doing an Ivy pull, hence a brief silence in the p.m. one day last week. There are some sparrows that are different coming to yard. Can't identify the little brown guys. Will do the Christmas bird count for Arlington - 6 parks. Red-headed Finches are here. A phlox bloomed last week. A Heath Aster bloomed a small flower. Salvia still in bloom - 1 spike. Milkweed in seed. Monarda in seed. Coreopsis and Coneflower in seed. Rabbits got some Asters. Planted four types of native shade plants and they are doing well. I've kept a big wood pile in the back for cover for birds and also let the bush by my window get bushy for cover. Saw a lot of Sparrows in the bush all puffed up. Providing Black oil Sunflower seeds, Safflower seeds, suet, and hulled peanuts. See city pigeons, American Crows, and White -breasted Nuthatch. Hairy and Downy woodpeckers and a small flitty bird - Red-crested Kinglet? Don't know. Goldfinches come to suet. Lots of Earthworms in the soil. No more spiders. Mice have come into the house so had to set traps. Mulching and putting beds to sleep. I put up a bat house. So that is the picture for December.

Other birds sighted at feeders: Norther Cardinals, Chickadees (unbanded), Mourning Doves, Starlings, Crows, BlueJays, Red-headed Finches, English Sparrows, a Sparrow with a Striped head, and a Carolina Wren with an Alum, Orange, and White band combo. The garden is sleeping now. Things are in seed, mulch is going in, beds are turned, and seed heads of flowering plants have been dead headed and put into the bed with a covering of mulch. Weeding is a big job. The feeders are kept full with safflower, Black OIl Sunflower, suet, bark butter balls with cayenne pepper, and hulled peanuts. There are four squirrels who come down to raid the feeders. Four large branches fell from the big Silver Maple and I fear we will need to take it down in the next 5 years. It is more than 60 years old. I have Oak, Chinquapin, and Maple growing. The Strawberry Bush provided flowers and food. The Beauty Berry bushes have berries. The pond is running and has minnows in it . Wlliamsburg Middle School Pond will be saved. A teacher is using my pond plan . Now is the time when I walk around the neighborhood and take pictures of birds nests and record the location - just for personal curiousity,

There is a lot of activity when peanuts, suet, safflower seed, and Thistle seed are put out at the two pole feeders.  Northern Cardinals visit.  House Wrens, English Sparrows, Blue Jays, Fish and American Crows, Pigeons, Goldfinches, and a Hummingbird.   Our terrier mix dog does not like Crows or large birds at the feeders and will bark and run down the stairs to scare them away.  He has also eaten an occasional vole, chipmunk, baby squirrel, and baby rabbit.

The blizzard began.  Snow falling.  Chickadee at feeder.  For three days up to the storm, feverish feeding at the feeders.  Even the feeder on the side wall of the house was filled and emptied in a day. BANDED AMRO: metal band on left leg. Most likely, this is "my" AMRO from the "Neighborhood Resight" project. The banded robin was last seen in August, when it had just the left metal band (the orange and blue bands had already fallen off the right leg). I could not quite read the band, so there is an outside chance that it is migratory robin with a band on its left leg and is NOT the bird for this project. There is a flock of migratory robins that visit the yard. This AMRO keeps to itself, and it is a female, so most likely it is the bird with band 1352-92507. I will try to read the band with a scope at some point, but seeing the bird again will be difficult.

This is first sighting of this bird since he was banded on 07/09/2017. Bird came to black oil sunflower seed feeder several times today. First day of snow, first sighting of bird. Probably coincidence, but I've wondered whether chickadees move in and out of area in relationship to weather after seeing chickadee 269087765 do so over span of a few winters.

The wren was singing at 10:00 am today in 39degree F. partly cloudy weather. Cardinals came later. Early in the morning in the dark of dawn, there are little dark birds smaller than Sparrows that come and feed on the ground. I have laid out straw from the Halloween bails I had to lay grass seed and encourage grass growth. These birds pick among the straw. I put out fresh thistle seed, thinking perhaps they were Goldfinches in winter phase. I can put a vegetable shortening and safflower seed feeder ball in the Glouca tree and watch the Goldfinches come to feed before the squirrels get it. It is cold and there is a slight wind.

Cloudy weather, 30 degrees F. Snow in the shape of little icey round balls, like granules, began to fall. I mulched and gardened, filled the feeders. The banded wren sang on the fence in the snow. This snow is slick. A second unbanded wren came to the feeder. About 8 English Sparrows, 2 Mourning doves, 1 White-breasted Nuthatch, a female unbanded Cardinal and a male unbanded Cardinal, 2 American Crows, about 4 Red-headed Finches, and some smaller Sparrows came to the feeder and fed intensely. They fed on seeds on the ground. I prepared some beds and lay out mulch. Pulled English Ivy. 4 Squirrels fed at the feeder. More mulching tomorrow.
At peanut butter mix+mealworm feeder

This individual has a very lame left leg. It is not able to use the leg or foot at all. Today, Adam Betuel of the Atlanta Audubon Society and a local rehab person came to my home to try to re-capture the bird and check out it's leg and to, hopefully, remove the bands. However, we were unable to capture the bird in mist nets.

I was laying mulch and pully invasivies when I turned to see the Carolina Wren at the feeder taking safflower seed. It suddenly jumped down and a flew in through the lattice and under the porch. Within a few seconds a Sharp-shinned Hawk flew into the big Sugar Maple in the tree. Who says winter is a dead time. Also, little wrens in the morning are Winter Wrens. Yellow-throated Sparrows are coming into the yard. I did the the Christmas Bird Count for Audubon for 6 parks in the area and put in the data. Tuckahoe Park and Lacy Woods had the most diversity. Tuckhaoe is only three blocks from the backyard. Tuckahoe had an immature Red-tailed Hawk perch in the big Oak trees, flocks of Robins, Carolina Wrens (unbanded), White-breasted Nutcatch, and Red-headed Finches, and Cardinals. Also, a Bald Eagle flew over the park headed west at a fast paste. I was with two other birders and they confirmed the sighting.
Spotted on backyard feeder. Healthy, active bird.

I'm putting in the bands that USED to be on his left leg just so my data will be accepted."

I have seen this bird throughout winter and on the coldest, windiest days. It goes to the feeder for suet. It flits under the porch, in the branch piles, up onto the feeders, quickly feeds, and then parts. It is 3/1/18. Spotted the first daffodil, Forthythia about to bloom, Snowdrops in bloom and small this year. Tulips are coming up. No Bluebells yet. Native Cherry Trees show some signs of budding. Yochino Cherry trees are in the early stage of blooming.They are predicted to bloom unfashionably early this year. A Yoshino tree down the street has bloomed. Have loaded feeders to watch for guests. Peanuts, Safflower, black oil sunflower seed, blocks of suet. I use Wild Birds Unlimited. Other brands are sour and the birds don't eat it. Have heard and seen a Song Sparrow this morning. Could not see the bands. Nesting activity in the box on the tree - Red-headed Finches. Have seen Mourning Doves, Cardinals - males vying for the feeders. Robins have arrived. Holly Berry trees have fruit. Squirrels are active. Mice in the shed attempted to get into the galvanized bin, but were caught. Have smelled Fox musk. Nuthatch comes to the peanuts. Starlings coming to suet. Will put out thistle for Gold Finches. Saw three flocks of Canada geese fly over the yard, direction - north. Have a tree crown cover map of Arlington. I can see my backyard. We are at 41% tree crown cover, down a few per cent. North Arlington is the darkest green. Losing trees to buiding big houses and no big trees. A flock of Sparrows is outside the window. It is cool - 53% and drizzling. Soil is loose and wet. Worms are two inches down. Ready to start planting but must wait for the Days of the Three Witches in May. Then can plant a garden. Must be patient. Birds are so heart warming. Neighbors watch too.

Feeding on suet on deck railing 2/24 14:30. Probably has been in yard all month, but a lot of other AMRO were here and chasing this bird away from the food. She has ONLY a metal AL bracelet on left leg at this point, the orange and blue bands are gone.The metal bracelet is very loose and hangs down on top of her foot (toes) but doesn't seem to bother her.
Resight by Diane Aiken, email message to RR 2-25-2018
This bird has been at the feeder all winter

Two tall feeders with 3-4 arms are laden with blocks of suet, suet balls, sunflower seeds, bark butter balls, and safflower seed. Feeders are different sizes and one has a plate to perch on. One feeder has a cage for the little guys to go in an get food. A window feeder outside the dining room window lets me see birds come for safflower seed. It was from this feeder last year that I saw a female Baltimore Oriole. But I did not see one yet. Many English Sparrows, Red-headed Finches, Starlings. 3 crows appeared. Squirrels munch on corn cobs to the back of the garden. The pond has water and I am putting water in an elevated bird bath basin. Have heard the Carolina Wren singing but it did not appear at the feeders during the window of the count or when I was counting. Also, around the block there is a Song Sparrow that likes to sing at the top of a particular tree in the native plant garden of a house. I will try to spot if it has bands. There are two unbanded male cardinals that look as if they are young coming to the feeders. They sometimes face off. Red feathers vibrant. In general, birds coming to feeders look fat, sleek, and healthy and show no eye problems. Daffodils blooming, Forsythia beginning to bloom, Teacup Magnolia just about to bloom, all trees show buds, Snowdrops fading, Saw one rabbit at night. Am noting small cup-like nests in small trees- must be last year's nests. The civic association is putting in green strips and planting small trees. NPR had a great show on Migratory Birds on 1A and it was good. Much talk about lighting, wind farms, and keeping cats in doors. All is ready for spring and I will bake a lamb cake for the family. We cannot wait. Let's hope our birds return.

OK.  I really looked at this Catbird.  He was different from the one yesterday.  He ate no-melt suet with pepper in it.  He drank from the shallow pan that is on a pole and to the back of the yard.  This pan is shallow, about 5 ft. 3 in. off the ground, has two rocks in it and is flushed with fresh water everyday.  His eyes look clear.  He looks fat and he is alert.
The usual birds are coming to the feeders:  Mourning Doves, Bluejays, Red-headed Finches, two pairs of Goldfinches, a White-breasted Nuthatch.  But where are the House Wrens and the other banded birds? I often wonder where the birds go to get food, if they do not come to these two feeders.  The feeders are run fairly consistently throughout the year.  The food is peanuts, suet, bark butter, and safflower seeds.  Occasionally, I add a cone of nuts.  Thistle seed for Goldfinches in a sack.  Black-eyed Susan is fading.  Cardinal Flower is fading.  The Goldfinches love to land on the 14 ft. tall Sunflowers and swing back and forth.  The small birds frequently hang out in the taller of three Persimmon trees, then fly to the feeder.  Also, Chickadees hang out in the mature pine tree nearest the feeder, then come to the feeder that is closest to that bough and return to the pine tree.  I have  observed Hummingbirds totally bypass the sugar water feeder, alight and sip at Monarda, then fly straight up to the canopy of the mature elm that is 60 years old.

Sited first Junco of the season.  Two non-banded Chicadees came to feeder.  Also, Mourning Dove, BlueJay, Red-headed Finch, Carolina Wren sings in backyard.  American Crows and Pigeons are coming too. 2  Male and female Cardinals.  Do not see bands, Male and female Goldfinches go to the net bag. The Garden is going to seed.  Sundflowers are not blooming.  One last Aster in bloom.  Texas Sage is blooming.  Native sunflower is in seed.  White Wood Aster is finishing.  One raised bed was upended by the dog and 2 dead mice were found near the bed.  Chipmunks are everywhere.  Squirrels come to the feeder, sometimes get in, hand upside down and eat the Safflower seed.  Food put out:  2 large feeders of Safflower seed for small birds.  1 net sack of Njer seed, 1 board for bark butter, two blocks of suet.  On second feeder, a peanut wreath, 1 cone, 3 small cylindar feeders for Northern Cardinals.

Few if any birds alighting on backyard feeders, though full of safflower seed, peanuts, and thistle.  The one Chickadee came only briefly and flew.  One Goldfinch fed and then left.  It is as if there is a stony pall over the yard.  Then I saw a fox at 5:30 p.m. walking on our street.  I followed it and watched as it attacked and got a squirrel.  I took a photo of the fox.  It has black tips on its ears.  Neighbors say they have seen two others.  But the black-tipped ears is the mark of this one.  It is sleek and fat.  It may be the fox I saw attack a group of 4 squirrels and successfully take one out and proceed to eat it behind a bush in my front yard at 9 a.m. I was seated in the front seat of my car about to go to work.  I just sat still in the car and then, it looked at me and we locked eyes.  Its eyes were golden yellow and dark around the edges.

I have been noticing a CACH coming to the suet feeder and feeding in an interesting way (pecking while hovering rather than perching). I have been noticing this for at least a few weeks. Today was the first time I noticed the bird was banded. Though hard to say for sure, it appears as if the birds right leg is injured. It is possible that the yellow band has begun to slip over the foot. I attempted today to capture the bird (I am a master bander) to see if it needs to be removed. I was unable to catch it today but will try later this week. I assumed the bird was yours only because that is the only active banding I know of at this location of this species. Please contact me if you want to discuss this further. If I am able to catch the bird I will email my findings to Bob Reitsma. My email is adam@atlantaaudubon.org. More info on the bird would be apprecaited
